  <h2 id="pageName">ScafBank Database</h2>
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>Motivation of ScafBank </h3>
    <p> ¡°scaffold hopping¡± or ¡°lead hopping¡± is a recently  emerged concept in medicinal chemistry field to describe the searching for  similar bioactivity compounds to their original hit structures. Many  computational approaches are invented to generate the heterogeneous structure  that may accompany with similar bioactivity and potency, such as de novo  design, virtual screening, pharmacophore searching, topology similarity  searching, shape similarity searching.</p>
    <p>Even though these  methods are empowering researchers to optimize their lead compounds or to  circumvent patent protected compounds, there¡¯s no public database contains such  invaluable materials of scaffolds and functional groups. Many public small  molecular databases are focused on the whole molecular level, such as ZINC  database, PubChem database. It is used for searching the entire molecule in the  database by similarity or substructures. Here we offer such database to researchers and hope can help them  &quot;hopping&quot; out. </p>
  </div>
  <div class="story">
    <h3>recursive scaffold analysis</h3>
    <p>The recursive  scaffold analysis implemented here is based on the idea in HirS system.  For the side chain trimmed molecule, the contiguous  fragment searching was conducted, for every fragment the basic ring scaffolds  were found and delete one by one to produce a new molecule (which may contain  several fragments, for every fragment, some atoms will become chain atoms). This  new molecule was subjected to a further recursive scaffold analysis. To  identify the basic ring scaffolds, the smallest set of smallest rings (SSSR)  method is used to indicate the ring atoms. If two rings are connected by one or  more atoms then they are associated together as one ring scaffold and this  continues until no ring can associate to others. The recursive scaffold process  was performed until only one ring system remains. Every resulted fragment was  added to the final scaffold list and written out as molecule. </p>
  </div>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
